== 媒體報導 ==

* The play [https://web.archive.org/web/20071026061321/http://www.aml-online.org/reviews/b/B199743.html ''Fire In The Bones''] (1978) by Thomas F. Rogers is a depiction of the massacre from the perspective of John D. Lee, and is based heavily on Juanita Brooks' research.
* The play [http://www.curtainup.com/2headed.html ''Two-Headed''] {{Wayback|url=http://www.curtainup.com/2headed.html |date=20061020033228 }} (2000) by Julie Jensen depicts two middle-aged Latter Day Saint (Mormon) women reflecting on the massacre that occurred when they were children.
* The film [http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0397048/ ''Burying the Past: Legacy of the Mountain Meadows Massacre''] {{Wayback|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0397048/ |date=20070205142905 }} (2004), directed by Brian F. Patrick, is a documentary of the event.
* The film [http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0473700/ ''September Dawn''] {{Wayback|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0473700/ |date=20070210051602 }} (2006), directed by Christopher Cain, depicts a love story set at the time of the massacre. [http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117957978.html?categoryid=13&cs=1] {{Wayback|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117957978.html?categoryid=13&cs=1 |date=20070715061515 }}
* the novel ''Red Water'' by Judith Freeman is a fictionalized account of John D. Lee's role in the massacre from the perspective of three of his nineteen wives.

